### 3. The "Threshold" Confusion
If you are looking for the **Threshold** (when the compiler actually kicks in), you are likely looking for these two:
| Flag | Meaning |
|---|---|
| **CompileThreshold** | The number of method invocations/branches needed to trigger JIT compilation (Standard in non-tiered mode). Default is usually **10,000** for C2. |
| **TieredCompileThresholds** | In modern Java (Tiered Compilation), there isn't just one threshold. The JVM uses complex heuristics to move code from Level 0 (interpreted) up to Level 4 (fully optimized). |
### Key Takeaway
For 99% of applications, **letting the JVM manage these is best.** The JVM is quite smart at sensing how much hardware it has.
> **Warning:** Manually setting CICompilerCount too high can lead to **CPU contention**, where your compiler threads are fighting your actual application threads for processing power, actually slowing down your "warm-up" time.
